# lucena-engine

[![license](https://img.shields.io/badge/license-AGPL--3.0-blue.svg)](LICENSE)
[![python](https://img.shields.io/badge/python-3.10%2B-blue.svg)](https://www.python.org/)
[![engine](https://img.shields.io/badge/engine-Stockfish%2018-informational.svg)](https://stockfishchess.org/)
[![maia](https://img.shields.io/badge/behaviour-Maia-9cf.svg)](https://github.com/CSSLab/maia3)

**Clean Python sessions for Stockfish and Maia, plus the eval vocabulary their
answers speak.**

`lucena-engine` wraps the two engines every serious chess application ends up
talking to — Stockfish for truth, Maia for human-move prediction — behind
persistent, deterministic UCI sessions, and gives their raw output a typed
vocabulary: `Score` (cp/mate, POV-correct negation), `Analysis`/`Line`
(multipv with principal variations), the lichess-verbatim win% model, and
move-quality glyph classification (`?!`, `?`, `??` …). Pure Python, zero
runtime dependencies, nothing linked — the GPL engines run as separate
subprocesses over UCI text.

> **v0.2.0 slimmed this package to exactly that wrapper.** Earlier releases
> also bundled a Rust board core, tactical detectors, fact sheets, and a gRPC
> server; those grew into private downstream layers of the
> [Lucena](https://github.com/distressedrook) coaching stack and left the
> public package. If you need board geometry, use
> [python-chess](https://github.com/niklasf/python-chess); this package
> deliberately contains no board so its AGPL grant stays trivially clean.

## Install

```bash
pip install lucena-engine
```

You bring the engines: a `stockfish` binary on `PATH` (or `LUCENA_STOCKFISH`),
and optionally a Maia policy endpoint via `LUCENA_MAIA` for human-move
prediction.

## Quickstart

```python
from lucena_engine import Engine, win_pct_from_score

with Engine(threads=1) as engine:          # persistent Stockfish session
    engine.new_game()                      # reproducible node-limited search
    a = engine.analyse(
        "r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/4p3/2B1P3/2N2N2/PPPP1PPP/R1B1K2R b KQkq - 0 4",
        nodes=500_000, multipv=2,
    )
    print(a.best.score, a.best.pv[:4])     # Score(cp=…) ['g8f6', …]
    print(round(win_pct_from_score(a.best.score), 1), "% for the side to move")
```

Determinism contract: `threads=1`, a node limit, and `new_game()` before each
query make `analyse` reproducible — the foundation for testable,
cache-friendly chess features.

## What's in the box

| module | what |
|---|---|
| `uci` | `Engine` — persistent Stockfish UCI session, version-pinned, `analyse(fen, nodes=\|movetime_ms=\|depth=, multipv=)` → `Analysis` |
| `maia` | `MaiaEngine` — rating-conditioned human-move prediction (top moves + policy) |
| `pool` | engine-process pooling primitives |
| `evalmodel` | `Score`, `win_pct` (lichess-verbatim), `classify` → glyphs, the `MISTAKE` threshold |
| `nnue` | parser for Stockfish's per-square NNUE `eval` output |

## License

AGPL-3.0-or-later. Stockfish and Maia are invoked **only as subprocesses over
UCI** — an arm's-length boundary, not linking; see
[THIRD-PARTY-NOTICES.md](THIRD-PARTY-NOTICES.md). A CI gate
(`tests/test_gpl_hygiene.py`) keeps copyleft imports out of the shipped
library. Contributions require the CLA ([CONTRIBUTING.md](CONTRIBUTING.md)).
